d": false, "mention": "methoxamine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9981935620307922, "span": {"begin": 668, "end": 679}}, {"id": ["mesh:D008729"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "methoxamine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9987868666648865, "span": {"begin": 909, "end": 920}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5443"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ACTH", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9936115145683289, "span": {"begin": 1016, "end": 1020}}, {"id": ["mesh:D006854"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cortisol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9987273812294006, "span": {"begin": 1025, "end": 1033}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:148"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "&alpha;1 receptors", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9556871652603149, "span": {"begin": 1068, "end": 1086}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "human", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9911865592002869, "span": {"begin": 1090, "end": 1095}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10116"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "rat", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9618553519248962, "span": {"begin": 1155, "end": 1158}}, {"id": ["mesh:D010656"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "phenylephrine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9988403916358948, "span": {"begin": 1167, "end": 1180}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5443"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ACTH", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9925550818443298, "span": {"begin": 1215, "end": 1219}}, {"id": ["mesh:D003345"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "corticosterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9940416216850281, "span": {"begin": 1258, "end": 1272}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:148"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "&alpha;1 receptors", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9730609655380249, "span": {"begin": 1307, "end": 1325}}, {"id": ["mesh:D010656"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "phenylephrine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9988290667533875, "span": {"begin": 1432, "end": 1445}}, {"id": ["mesh:D003345"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "corticosterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9659525156021118, "span": {"begin": 1539, "end": 1553}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:148"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "&alpha;1 receptors", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9715361595153809, "span": {"begin": 1585, "end": 1603}}, {"id": ["mesh:D008729"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Methoxamine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9993280172348022, "span": {"begin": 1667, "end": 1678}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5443"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ACTH", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.919562816619873, "span": {"begin": 1729, "end": 1733}}, {"id": ["mesh:D006854"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cortisol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9981175661087036, "span": {"begin": 1768, "end": 1776}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:148"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "alpha-1-adrenergic receptors", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9955881237983704, "span": {"begin": 1856, "end": 1884}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "HPA axis", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.4898378551006317, "span": {"begin": 1908, "end": 1916}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "humans", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9893903136253357, "span": {"begin": 1920, "end": 1926}}], "text": "Administration of methoxamine in humans has demonstrated significant activation of the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis, with increased ACTH and subsequent elevation of plasma cortisol in men, showing that stimulation of &alpha;1-adrenergic receptors can directly modulate glucocorticoid secretion (Al-Damluji, 1987);  Alpha-1 adrenergic stimulation by methoxamine resulted in a consistent increase in cortisol, while pharmacological blockade of alpha-1 receptors reduced this response, reinforcing the functional role of these receptors in the control of the HPA axis in humans&nbsp;(Al-Damluji, 1987);  It has been observed that the cortisol and ACTH response to methoxamine varies according to the circadian rhythm, being more intense in the morning, indicating that the sensitivity of the HPA axis to &alpha;1 stimulation is dependent on the basal physiological state (Naylor, 1988);  Stimulation with methoxamine also confirmed direct modulation of the pituitary-adrenal axis, with a concomitant increase in ACTH and cortisol, reinforcing the participation of &alpha;1 receptors in human neuroendocrine regulation. (Radant, 1992)  In experimental rat models, phenylephrine induced a significant increase in ACTH, leading to a subsequent elevation of corticosterone, demonstrating that activation of &alpha;1 receptors is sufficient to activate the complete HPA axis. (Proulx-Ferland, 1982);  Further studies have shown that phenylephrine activates the HPA axis under both basal and stress conditions, with a consistent increase in corticosterone, indicating a relevant role of &alpha;1 receptors in the adaptive stress response&nbsp;(Gadek-Michalska, 2008);  Methoxamine infusion induced a significant increase in plasma ACTH levels (peak at 75 min) and serum cortisol (peak at 120 min) in male volunteers, demonstrating that direct stimulation of alpha-1-adrenergic receptors strongly activates the HPA axis in humans (Delitala et al, 1994).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 16:19:37 +0000 2026"}